06428nam a22009615i 9780812205961DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112010pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013941935  a97808122059617 a10.9783/97808122059612doi  a(DE-B1597)449430  a(OCoLC)979724108  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHT168.P43 7aARC0100002bisacsh04a307.1/2160974811090422200aImagining Philadelphia :bEdmund Bacon and the Future of the City /ced. by Scott Gabriel Knowles. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (184 p.) :b26 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Revisiting Edmund Bacon’s Vision for the City -- tChapter One. Philadelphia in the Year 2009 -- tChapter Two. Salesman of Ideas: The Life Experiences That Shaped Edmund Bacon -- tChapter Three. A Utopian, a Utopianist, or Whatever the Heck It Is: Edmund Bacon and the Complexity of the City -- tChapter Four. Staying Too Long at the Fair: Philadelphia Planning and the Debacle of 1976 -- tChapter Five. Philadelphia in the Year 2059 -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tContributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen Philadelphia's iconoclastic city planner Edmund N. Bacon looked into his crystal ball in 1959, he saw a remarkable vision: "Philadelphia as an unmatched expression of the vitality of American technology and culture." In that year Bacon penned an essay for Greater Philadelphia Magazine, originally entitled "Philadelphia in the Year 2009," in which he imagined a city remade, modernized in time to host the 1976 Philadelphia World's Fair and Bicentennial celebration, an event that would be a catalyst for a golden age of urban renewal.What Bacon did not predict was the long, bitter period of economic decline, population dispersal, and racial confrontation that Philadelphia was about to enter. As such, his essay comes to us as a time capsule, a message from one of the city's most influential and controversial shapers that prompts discussions of what was, what might have been, and what could yet be in the city's future.Imagining Philadelphia brings together Bacon's original essay, reprinted here for the first time in fifty years, and a set of original essays on the past, present, and future of urban planning in Philadelphia. In addition to examining Bacon and his motivations for writing the piece, the essays assess the wider context of Philadelphia's planning, architecture, and real estate communities at the time, how city officials were reacting to economic decline, what national precedents shaped Bacon's faith in grand forms of urban renewal, and whether or not it is desirable or even possible to adopt similarly ambitious visions for contemporary urban planning and economic development. The volume closes with a vision of what Philadelphia might look like fifty years from now.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCity plannerszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiavBiography. 0aCity planningzPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistoryx20th century. 0aCity planningzPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aCity planningzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aCity planningzUnited StatesxCase studies. 4aArchitecture. 7aARCHITECTURE / Urban & Land Use Planning.2bisacsh  aArchitecture.  aPublic Policy.  aReligious Studies.  aUrban Studies.1 aBacon, Edmund N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBirch, Eugenie L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeller, Gregory L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnowles, Scott Gabriel, econtri